    {
      "id": "6aaab257dfa623fdef3c017f9929377ac29e8443",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-09-30 22:23:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHm.  The idea of something variable rather than fixed is appealing, but that one probably wouldn't work, and I haven't thought of another.\n\nThe key here is that this should be as small as possible (so we start sending RPCs in the random case), while being >= the number of CPUs doing writes to this stripe of this particular object.\n\nThis shouldn't be very many anyway, and if it is, they'll get bad performance for other reasons.  We could do 8 instead of 4 to create a bit more headroom, but then in the random case, we would only start RPCs after we had 128 MiB (assuming 16 MiB RPCs) of dirty data.\n\nIf there are many active CPUs, it's likely that they're either writing FPP, writing mostly (or entirely) to other stripes, or they're not doing I/O.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0750f1b0d8b5ac6619939263a2483e612a49d9dc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-01 02:36:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> The idea of something variable rather than fixed is appealing,\n > but that one probably wouldn't work, and I haven't thought of\n > another.\n\nIf we use num_active_cpus() with some upper limit (eg. 64?) then we would get up to 64MB of dirty pages on the client before an RPC was formed. I don't think that is so bad. This gives some opportunity for merging on the client, if it is a random-but-dense write workload, and allows some piecewise ordering of pages within the file. \n\n > This shouldn't be very many anyway, and if it is, they'll get bad\n > performance for other reasons.  We could do 8 instead of 4 to\n > create a bit more headroom, but then in the random case, we would\n > only start RPCs after we had 128 MiB (assuming 16 MiB RPCs) of\n > dirty data.\n \nEven with 16 MB RPC size, we cap the number of fragments in a single RPC to 256 (I think) for two reasons:\n- limit the size of the RPC request itself, otherwise with 16MB RPCs we would have 4096 niobuf_remote structs in the request, which is 64KB\n- add concurrency to the RPC processing. With random IO there is little chance for page merges on the client, but submitting more RPCs to the OSS for processing concurrently allows more threads/CPUs to be active in parallel.  \n\nI guess the proof is in the pudding - did you get any chance to benchmark this before/after the patch?   It may not affect a many-client write bandwidth, but I suspect it would improve single-client write latency.  Something like what Ihara posted in LU-11164  should be run, maybe with fake_io so that you are measuring client performance instead of server performance.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "4c798e6b691feafc8d9de07903ef39583c921b89",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-10-01 15:24:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAndreas,\n\nRemember that in general max_pages_per_rpc is now either 1024/4 MiB or 4096/16 MiB, so 64*4 = 256 MiB [large but maybe OK] and 64*16 = 1024 MiB [oof].\n\nSo 4*max_pages_per_rpc is either going to be 16 or 64 in most future configs (those we'd expect to see this patch).  So perhaps 8 would be better?  It depends a lot on what max_pages_per_rpc is, since we've got such a broad range now.\n\nPerhaps a % of max_dirty_mb would be better?  Say, 1/8 of it, for binary ratios.\n\nBut I agree about benchmarking, more on that in a moment.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "523d00cd47b88831ad8f9b35bbfc80e62ce08bb7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-10-01 15:31:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI plan to get benchmark data soon and will put some in the commit.\n\nI figured it's worth describing the scenario I'm trying to avoid.  Consider a *very* large sparse file and a system with 2 GiB max_dirty_mb.  That system will allow 2 GiB of dirty data to build up before sending any RPCs, then will send as much as max_rpcs_in_flight and the fragments limit you referenced allows.  (So in the worst case it would be as little as 1 MiB per RPC, 4096*256.)\n\nThose RPCs will go out *very* fast since the data is already in cache.  Very nearly all at once.\n\nThen the OSS/OST will process them, in parallel, and they will all complete around roughly the same time.  The client - which has just been waiting for this - will then refill the cache space this freed up, then do this \"burst\" of RPCs again when the limit is hit.\n\nSo that's the problem - We want RPCs in flight all the time.  Ideally, the client is constantly submitting RPCs and the server constantly has RPCs to write out.  (Obviously in this scenario something is the bottleneck, but the key is both going on at the same time, as much as possible.)\n\nI've verified this behavior by looking at stats, etc, but I need to do benchmarks to verify the benefit.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "6b0ee8e90cb8effa9e6cb31670839d1e5de7ea52",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-01 16:53:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(2 comments)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ca5dcaebcea5f2314b4e2e64bf844e84042d7154",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-10-01 16:59:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f52e5b85f45fa31bb7d4b2d520e1ffd66ba614f5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-06 11:46:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nPatrick, did you get any chance to run a performance test on this patch?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a3b6f1f89edada9d69f67324047512de1424e9b9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-06-04 05:38:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nWith the increase if PTLRPC_MAX_BRW_PAGES to 64MB in patch https://review.whamcloud.com/34042 \"LU-11526 rpc: support maximum 64MB I/O RPC\", it makes sense to get this patch updated and landed for 2.13.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8faeca22a355e06d2b8f135a863603cca77e4ea9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-04 15:41:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAndreas,\n\nSo I never updated this patch with it (sorry), but I eventually decided there was little or no performance to be gained here.  For every case where starting RPCs earlier is good, it seems like there's one where we could've gotten better I/O by waiting to drain the file until we hit the cache and/or grant limits.  (Also, the grant limit for small sparse writes is much less than 2 GiB of actual data due to including extent overhead on essentially every write.)\n\nSo I don't think this patch will do harm, but I'm not sure it helps much either.  Is there a reason to want it beyond the original goal of performance improvement?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "fff4f4c8da7a66372c2fb5b33e716f3fb8ce33b5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-06-05 00:31:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Andreas,\n > \n > So I never updated this patch with it (sorry), but I eventually\n > decided there was little or no performance to be gained here.  For\n > every case where starting RPCs earlier is good, it seems like\n > there's one where we could've gotten better I/O by waiting to drain\n > the file until we hit the cache and/or grant limits.  (Also, the\n > grant limit for small sparse writes is much less than 2 GiB of\n > actual data due to including extent overhead on essentially every\n > write.)\n > \n > So I don't think this patch will do harm, but I'm not sure it helps\n > much either.  Is there a reason to want it beyond the original goal\n > of performance improvement?\n\nThe main improvement I'm interested in is to reduce the maximum number of fragments for random IO.  I don't think there is a benefit to packing 16k random 4KB pages into a single RPC.  This has several bad effects:\n- consumes a huge amount of grant without it being returned quickly\n- consumes a large number of journal credits, because 4KB random writes represent the worst-case allocation for files\n- prevents merging of IOs at the server",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "62a6ba5080d2259052d6ebf4f6480385c0efe077",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-05 17:04:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nMakes sense - This will require some other tweaks, but it makes sense to do here.  I'll take that on in a new version of this patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "718ce5b71f43ef974a1366767c58529f5b73a0d5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-08-16 16:45:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nThe theory of i/o performance I had in mind when I created this appears to be wrong...  I'd like to abandon it, but can't since it's from my old account. :)\n\nBasically, it's reasonable to wait for the cache limit to be hit, and it doesn't take long.  This seems to be an unnecessary optimization.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "348f36c5bae870da59db2612b63c5530ed14a37f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-09-06 04:58:32.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
